Read this first
How this assignment works
Use any AI tool for the entire build — capture pipeline, chunking, embeddings, retrieval, generation, UI. Wiring up a RAG stack is not the focus.

What we grade
What we actually grade: an evaluation built from your own real browsing, and the messy problems that only show up on the world's least clean corpus — a human's actual reading. No dataset knows what you'll read this fortnight, whether your parser strips a specific site's chrome, or which near-duplicate visits collapse. In the live follow-up you ask your index a fresh question and we watch it retrieve. An eval you didn't genuinely verify is the one instant-fail.

The build
What you build
A Manifest V3 Chrome extension plus a local RAG pipeline that quietly indexes the pages you read and answers questions with citations back into your history — "you read this on example.com, three days ago."

Capture. Grab the readable content of pages you visit, under an allow/block model you control.
Clean. Strip nav, ads, and boilerplate down to the real content — parsing fidelity matters.
Dedup. Collapse re-visits, near-identical pages, and repeated SPA states.
Index. Chunk → embed (local) → store in a local vector store / IndexedDB.
Ask. Answer natural-language questions with citations; clicking one reopens the exact source.
Control. Pause capture, exclude sites, delete an entry, wipe the whole index — all one click away.
Everything runs locally by default. If you never read about something, the right answer is "not in your history," not a confident guess.

Fieldwork
Test it against your real fortnight
Live corpus. Run capture over your genuine day-to-day browsing for an extended period — aim for around two weeks of real use. You cannot fabricate what you'll actually read.
Hand-build a 30-question eval with verified answers drawn from that corpus. Include multi-hop (combine two+ pages), negative cases (things you never read → "not found"), and time-scoped ("what did I read about X last week"). Record ground truth + source location for each.
Measure retrieval and answer quality across the eval. Score each: correct / partial / wrong / hallucinated.
Wrestle the real problems and report them: boilerplate-stripping fidelity, near-duplicate dedup, half-loaded SPA capture, and your privacy/threat model. Improve one component and show the measured lift.
Evidence
Deliverables
The extension + local-RAG repo + README (install, one-command eval run, the privacy model)
eval/questions.json — 30 questions with ground truths and source locations (redact anything private)
eval/logs/ — per-question retrieved chunks + answer + score, for each configuration
FINDINGS.md — results table · error analysis (5 most interesting failures, with the retrieved chunks) · the one improvement's before/after · one surprise · a privacy/threat-model section · an AI-usage note
A short demo: ask it 3 live questions, including one negative case
