Read this first
How this assignment works
Use any AI tool for the entire build. Writing the extension is not the focus — we do this daily and expect you to.

What we grade
What we actually grade: the reviews you label by hand, and the changes you observe by waiting. Whether a specific real review is genuine, and whether a product gets a burst of fake ones next week, is live signal that exists in no dataset. In the live follow-up we ask why you labeled a given review the way you did. Fabricated findings — an invented burst most of all — are the one instant-fail.

The build
What you build
A Manifest V3 Chrome extension that, on any product / app / listing page, collects the visible reviews and surfaces authenticity signals:

Rating–text mismatch. Five stars with negative wording, or the reverse — caught with on-device sentiment.
Templated & duplicated phrasing. Near-identical sentences recurring across reviewers.
Temporal bursts. Clusters of reviews arriving in a suspiciously short window.
Reviewer patterns. Where visible: brand-new accounts, single-review profiles, verified-purchase status.
A "read this skeptically" summary. An overall read, with the specific reviews it's based on cited.
Run sentiment on-device with Transformers.js — no server, no key. Handle pagination and lazy-loaded reviews. Be explicit about what you can't see: most sites hide reviewer history, and your tool should say so rather than pretend.

Fieldwork
Label real reviews, then watch real products
Hand-labeled corpus. Across ~10 real products, label a set of reviews as genuine / suspicious / can't-tell, with your reasoning. You are the ground truth — be ready to defend any single label.
Measure each signal for precision and recall against your labels, and report where signals disagree.
Longitudinal watch. Monitor 5 products' review streams over an extended window and capture the time series. Report any real injection burst, velocity change, or rating drift you actually observed — data you can only get by waiting.
Signal-to-noise. How often did a flag correspond to something real? Build the taxonomy of noise you learned to suppress.
