3.
Brief · ToS / privacy-policy risk flagger
The Fine-Print Redline
Build a tool that flags the risky clauses in a site's terms — then prove it's right by reading the fine print yourself.

Chrome Extension · MV3
$0 — local model path
Solo build
Repo + clause corpus + demo
Read this first
How this assignment works
Use any AI tool for the entire build. Wiring up extraction, summarization, and flagging is not the focus.

What we grade
What we actually grade: reading the policies yourself and deciding what's actually predatory. An LLM can draft candidate labels — but the ground truth of "does this clause exist, and is it genuinely risky or standard boilerplate?" is a judgment you make by reading the document. In the live follow-up we point your tool at a policy you didn't pick and check every flag against the real text. A confident flag for a clause that isn't there is the worst outcome in this brief.

The build
What you build
A Manifest V3 Chrome extension that, on any site, locates and extracts the Terms of Service / Privacy Policy, summarizes it in plain language, and flags risky clauses — each flag quoting the exact passage it's based on. Cover these risk categories at minimum:

Data sale / third-party sharing. Your data sold or handed to partners and brokers.
Forced arbitration / class-action waiver. You give up the right to sue or join a class action.
Auto-renewal / negative-option billing. Charges continue unless you actively cancel.
Broad content license. They can reuse, sublicense, or train on what you upload.
Unilateral change. "We may amend these terms at any time," often without notice.
Vague or long data retention. Your data kept indefinitely, or for undefined periods.
The real engineering problems: locating the policy, parsing very long documents, and — above all — not inventing clauses that aren't there. A grounded flag with a citation beats a confident summary every time.

Fieldwork
Read the policies, then hold your tool to what they say
Labeled clause corpus from ~15 real policies. Extract clauses, classify each risky / standard by category, and record the exact source location. You verify every label by reading the policy. An LLM may draft; the ground truth is yours.
Measure precision and recall against your labels, per category.
Hallucination audit. Measure how often your tool flags a clause that isn't in the document, or mis-quotes one. Report this number prominently — grounding honesty is the whole game.
The judgment call. "Predatory vs. standard boilerplate" is real — arbitration clauses are near-universal; is that a flag or just reality? Pick your five hardest and argue each.
Iterate on grounding/retrieval, then re-measure — especially the hallucination rate.
Evidence
Deliverables
The extension repo + README (load-unpacked, permissions rationale, what's implemented, known limits)
corpus/ — labeled clauses: text + category + risk label + source location
FINDINGS.md — precision/recall · hallucination rate · your five hardest calls · before/after iteration · one surprise · an AI-usage note
A short demo: run it on a live policy and show a grounded flag with its citation
